Miracle Seed: Biased Expectations, Complementary Input Use and the Dynamics
 of Smallholder Technology Adoption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Farmers that try out agricultural technologies, such as improved seed varieties
 obtained from agro-input dealers, may hold unrealistic expectations about
 this technology.
 The fact that they paid a significant price for certain traits of the technolog
y, such as higher yield or pest resistance, may lead them to invest less
 in complementary inputs such as fertilizer and reduce management practices
 such weeding.
 Subsequent disappointment about the performance of the technology may then
 be attributed to the technology itself, instead of to the reduced use of
 complementary inputs and effort, resulting in dis-adoption.
 We provide a simple model of technology adoption and derive a cluster of
 predictions.
 To test these predictions, we set up a field experiment among 3,500 maize
 farmers in Uganda.
 In the experiment, a treatment group gets explicit information on the importanc
e of combining improved technologies and recommended farming practices.
 We find some evidence that our message scares farmers away from commercial
 seed, back to local land-races.
 The results suggest that extension workers, and industry in particular,
 should focus on technology adoption as a package of complementary inputs
 and efforts, instead of marketing a single technology.
\end_layout

