 Our theory suggests that in response to being sensitized about the importance
 of using complementary inputs and cultivation practices, less farmers would
 use improved seed varieties from agro-input dealers, and revert to farmer
 saved landraces.
 We find that the coefficients go in the right direction, however, we only
 find a significant difference for the share of farmers that planted recycled
 seed at midline.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The differences in the fourth column are for all farmers.
 However, the treatment is likely not relevant to all farmers: some farmers
 may not adopt because of other reasons than the ones we conjecture.
 For instance, they may simply not have access to seed, or access to credit
 may be the primary constraint.
 In the fourth column, we thus restrict the sample to only those farmers
 that adopted in at baseline to investigate heterogeneous response to the
 treatment.
 We do indeed see effects become stronger if we restrict attention to this
 subgroup.
\end_layout

